^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's first talk about whether or not Babs should have transferred. It is true that with a weak hand, you are almost always better off in the weak hand's long suit because then the long suit will take some extra tricks without your needing entries to run the suit. That is why, with long spades or long hearts, you always transfer over a 1N opener, even with a weak hand. |
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, the problem with transferring to a minor is you are forced to play at the 3 level. Therefore, the question is, are you more likely to take 9 tricks in the minor or 7 tricks at NT and which is likely to do down less. That is not always an easy question to answer. In this case, I agree with Babs decision to transfer because she has a 6 card suit and 0 HCP. |
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So it is very unlikely Dave can make 1N. And if Dave happens to have 3 (or even 4) nice clubs, 3@C might have plays. On the other hand, in general, I find people transfer too much to 3 of a minor to play even with a 6 card suit, with 4-7 HCP, you are almost always better off.|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play Dave can give himself more chances. At the very least, he can lead low towards his @CK hoping Gail has the @CA. He does have diamond ruffs to get to dummy. He can also just duck the first heart, win the 2nd heart, and ruff 2 hearts in his hand because he has some reasonable spots. So I think with a different line of play, 3@C will make.|
